Doc Dell<br><br>
You wrote,<br>
&quot;I am curious as to why you have not read threads and posts previous to your first post.&quot;<br><br>
If you are referring to the first time I posted here, it was in dialog on the theme or the thread that interested me at that time. You will see that same pattern throughout my postings, stories submitted that correspond with the topic (s) being discussed or shared or to current news stories.<br><br>
Since then I have gone back and read many posts, I did it because I wanted to know who it was I was conversing with. To get to know former servicemen, as co-patriots an unpopular war, to see what and where they are today. Shared experiences brings a wealth of healing, to many of us who may still see things vague and unsure. Who, question what or why we did the things we did. <br><br>
I did read the post whoĺs who, searching for answers to give an individual the respect they deserve. It was there I first notice Spatzĺ reference to you as not willing to give your real name. Thatĺs fine with me, I have no trouble with that.  It only takes time to know who is real and who is not. My book agent can easily substantiate what I have written as true not only by the Marine Corps after action reports  but also by contacting witnesses that were there as well. I have nothing to hide. <br><br>
I question individuals that post with a sincerity to understand them, I questioned Class Lass identity at first because her post reflected certain qualities that arose my police and analytical suspicions. She has, since then earned my deepest respect, while I have not inquired any more into her background or identity. <br><br>
In life I have learned that some have resented what I have said, because they see themselves as less for not having done what I did. I never did it for glory, recognition or any other selfish motives, the book is not like that, I am not like that. I just happened to be there at the right time for what ever reason and for that I am deeply grateful and proud of.  I feel I have been given a great opportunity in life and because of this, much more is required of what I do with it. I respect and honor others that did their part in Vietnam, and respect those that did not fight because of their religious convictions, that I can understand. <br><br>
It was in searching for those who were posting that I first noticed the abuse by a so-called professional psychologist, I saw him setting up Vietnam veterans for his own selfish amusement. He was not a protestor one could have an open dialog with. My former training as a Police officer, a Crime Analysis, and a Christian counselor compelled me to investigate, to question, to challenge an individuals credentials, because of the hurt he was causing. Because I saw, what he posted was not substantiate by what he stated he was. <br><br>
You may recall that I was willing to meet with Mr. Spatz for lunch right from the beginning, I held no animosity toward him as a war protestor, but its the deceitfulness that emerged after that that no longer warrants a response from me. He lost all respect I may have had for him at one time.<br><br>
*I* choose to ignore him and have never answered any of his E-mails. I have chosen to ignore him not because he gets to me, to tell you the truth, he doesn't and never has. To me it is just silly, childish stuff compared to what I have dealt with. Like you ôThe problem that I see is that whatever good is posted, the garbage with the anons detract from it.ö  Not answering him remains the best form of retaining the integrity of this site. Some posting from anon or others do require an answer, least others reading the post for the first time see it as a site where Vietnam veteran bashing is tolerated, supported and accepted.<br><br>
I have read many books written by the protestors of the war and understand their convictions and motivations. I also have a background in studying and analyzing some of the motives behind some individuals involved in the anti-war movement during that time and know some of which their desires and motives were to destroy this country  from within. Enough said on that. <br><br>
Unfortunately there are no clear fields of fire on this site and if we are to have meaningful dialog we need to be able to share what we have gone through and what we go through each day. When a parasite roams close by, you donĺt show him an open wound. You keep it covered and or hidden, away from the flies and leeches of life. And that is what has happened here. Though in Nam after awhile I used to pick up the leeches and tell them to eat. Thatĺs when you no longer cared if you lived or died. You became numb to the pain and suffering after awhile and didnĺt care anymore. <br><br>
This site is not like that. There are a lot of caring and giving Vietnam veterans here that are willing to lend a listening ear to protestors and to share with other veterans from their experiences in spite of the leeches swimming in the rice paddy water. We still wade in to help another veteran out of the muddy rice paddy fields, when we can. That is why I am here, why I remain, why I sahre my thoughts.<br><br>
I appreciate your questions and correspondence and look forward to much more.<br><br>
In Peace and War<br>
Cook <br><br>
